
The files MetaFormulas.sml and MetaIn.sml contain some examples for the use
of meta formulas in ConceptBase.

MetaFormulas.sml
================

The "Single" meta formula requires that every attribute in
the category "single" has at most one instance.


The "Necessary" meta formula requires that every attribute in
the category "necessary" has at most one instance.


The "Cardinality" meta formula requires that every attribute in
the category "cardinality" has at least "min" instances and at
most "max" instances. "min" and "max" are set by the attributes
min and max of the attribute class "Proposition!cardinality".

Example:

The following example requires that the salary attribute of an
employee has at least 2 and at most 3 values.

Class Employee with
attribute,cardinality,necessary
	salary : Integer
end

Employee!salary with
min
	min : 2
max
	max : 3
end


MetaIn.sml
==========

This file contains the definition of a metaIn predicate. An object o
is a meta instance of the meta class m, if there exists class c,
o is an instance of c, and c is an instance of the meta class m.

InverseOf.sml
=============
  	  	  	
This models shows how to declare one attribute to be the inverse of another attribute.


LinkSemantics.sml
=================	

Some definitions for relation properties using the constraint/rule mechanism of 
ConceptBase.
	
LinkSemantics2.sml
==================	

A shortened and more readable version of LinksSemantics.sml. Shows the 
combination of the semantics of generic relation properties. Note that the 
hasAncestor relation is defined to be anti-symmetric and transitive whereas the 
knows relation is transitive, symmetric and reflexive. ConceptBase will ensure 
the semantics via the generic definitions.
	
TransitiveClosureOf.sml
=======================

This example shows how to define an attribute B to be the transitive closure of 
some other attribute A. For example, ancestor is the transitive closure of 
parent.
